Here are **specific mobile (600px) padding reductions** targeting the four areas you called out. These are dropin overrides inside your existing `@media (max-width: 600px)` block.

---

##  1) Chat container padding
Your `.chat-container` still uses desktop padding (20px 26px). Tighten it for 325px screens.

```css
@media (max-width: 600px) {
  .chat-container {
    padding: 12px 14px; /* was 20px 26px */
  }
}
```

---

##  2) User message bubble padding
Reduce internal padding and width so it doesnt eat the viewport. Also tighten vertical spacing.

```css
@media (max-width: 600px) {
  .message {
    padding: 12px 14px;  /* was 18px 22px */
    margin: 8px 0;       /* was 12px 0 */
    width: 100%;
    max-width: 100%;
  }

  .message.user {
    margin-left: auto;
  }
}
```

---

##  3) Assistant response area padding
This uses `.message.assistant` as container. Reduce padding and tighten line height for mobile legibility.

```css
@media (max-width: 600px) {
  .message.assistant {
    padding: 12px 14px;  /* match user bubble */
    line-height: 1.6;    /* was 1.8 */
  }

  .message.assistant h3 {
    padding: 8px 10px;   /* was 10px 14px */
  }
}
```

---

##  4) Horse cards within response
You have two `.horse-card` definitions (old + new). The *new* one is larger (padding 24px, margin 24px). Override both by targeting the class directly on mobile.

```css
@media (max-width: 600px) {
  .horse-card {
    padding: 14px;       /* was 24px */
    margin: 12px 0;      /* was 24px 0 */
    border-radius: 8px;  /* slightly tighter */
  }

  .horse-card-image {
    width: 120px;        /* was 140px */
    height: 120px;
  }

  .horse-card-content {
    gap: 8px;            /* was 12px */
  }
}
```

